[{"_1":2},"llms/full",{"_3":4},"data","# gRPC Tunnel Design (/docs/architecture/grpc-tunnel)\n\n\n\ngRPC Tunnel Design [#grpc-tunnel-design]\n\nThe current transport uses one long-lived gRPC stream per active tunnel.\n\nBenefits:\n\n* outbound-only client connectivity\n* low-latency server-to-client request dispatch\n* room for heartbeats and future stream extensions\n* simpler operator deployment than request polling\n\nCurrent limitations:\n\n* WebSocket support is still pending\n* tunnel metadata is not yet fully server-owned\n\n\n# Architecture / Spec (/docs/architecture)\n\n\n\nArchitecture / Spec [#architecture--spec]\n\nThe current implementation uses:\n\n* public HTTP ingress on the server\n* a gRPC tunnel stream from client to server\n* request forwarding over that stream\n* server-side admin APIs and UI\n\nArchitecture Pages [#architecture-pages]\n\n* [Traffic Flow](/docs/architecture/traffic-flow)\n* [gRPC Tunnel Design](/docs/architecture/grpc-tunnel)\n* [Rewrite Direction](/docs/architecture/rewrite-direction)\n\n\n# Rewrite Direction (/docs/architecture/rewrite-direction)\n\n\n\nRewrite Direction [#rewrite-direction]\n\nThe rewrite target is a stronger tunnel platform with:\n\n* server-owned tunnel records\n* OIDC-based human authentication\n* separate agent credentials for machine tunnel registration\n* better observability and request logs\n* access controls at ingress\n* WebSocket support\n\nThe current codebase now includes the first persistence foundation:\n\n* SQLite-backed tunnel records\n* persisted request logs\n* stronger client runtime-state cleanup\n\n\n# Traffic Flow (/docs/architecture/traffic-flow)\n\n\n\nTraffic Flow [#traffic-flow]\n\nCurrent flow:\n\n1. Client opens a gRPC stream to the server.\n2. Client registers a hostname.\n3. Browser sends a request to `https://<hostname>`.\n4. Server looks up the active tunnel.\n5. Server sends a proxied request over the stream.\n6. Client forwards that request to the local app.\n7. Client returns the response over the stream.\n8. Server returns that response to the browser.\n\nThis model works behind NAT because the client initiates the outbound connection.\n\n\n# CLI Device Flow (/docs/authentication/device-flow)\n\n\n\nCLI Device Flow [#cli-device-flow]\n\nLog in from the CLI:\n\n```bash\nexport FWDX_SERVER=https://tunnel.example.com\nfwdx login\n```\n\nThe CLI prints:\n\n* verification URL\n* user code\n* direct verification URL when the provider exposes one\n\nAfter approval:\n\n```bash\nfwdx whoami\n```\n\nManagement commands reuse the stored session:\n\n```bash\nfwdx manage tunnels --server https://tunnel.example.com\nfwdx domains add my.domain --server https://tunnel.example.com\n```\n\nThe stored session lives at:\n\n```text\n~/.fwdx/auth.json\n```\n\n\n# Authentication (/docs/authentication)\n\n\n\nAuthentication [#authentication]\n\n`fwdx` now has a split auth model:\n\n* humans authenticate with OIDC\n* tunnel runtimes authenticate with per-agent credentials\n\nHuman auth [#human-auth]\n\n* Admin UI: OIDC authorization code flow with PKCE\n* CLI: OIDC device authorization flow via `fwdx login`\n\nTunnel runtime auth [#tunnel-runtime-auth]\n\nTunnel clients do not use a shared global runtime token anymore.\n\n* the server issues a credential to a named agent\n* tunnel definitions are stored on the server and assigned to an agent\n* the local client stores its assigned agent credential in `~/.fwdx/client.json`\n\nPages [#pages]\n\n* [OIDC UI Login](/docs/authentication/oidc-ui)\n* [CLI Device Flow](/docs/authentication/device-flow)\n\n\n# OIDC UI Login (/docs/authentication/oidc-ui)\n\n\n\nOIDC UI Login [#oidc-ui-login]\n\nRequired server settings:\n\n```bash\nexport FWDX_OIDC_ISSUER=https://issuer.example.com\nexport FWDX_OIDC_CLIENT_ID=fwdx-web\nexport FWDX_OIDC_CLIENT_SECRET=your-secret\nexport FWDX_OIDC_REDIRECT_URL=https://tunnel.example.com/auth/oidc/callback\nexport FWDX_OIDC_ADMIN_EMAILS=admin@example.com\n```\n\nThe redirect URL must point back to the `fwdx` server:\n\n```text\nhttps://tunnel.example.com/auth/oidc/callback\n```\n\nOnce configured, visit:\n\n```text\nhttps://tunnel.example.com/admin/ui\n```\n\nThe UI redirects to the OIDC provider and returns with a session cookie issued by `fwdx`.\n\n\n# CLI Usage (/docs/cli)\n\n\n\nCLI Usage [#cli-usage]\n\nThe current CLI has four areas:\n\n* server startup\n* OIDC login\n* admin management\n* tunnel lifecycle\n\nServer [#server]\n\n```bash\nfwdx serve \\\n  --hostname tunnel.example.com \\\n  --oidc-issuer https://issuer.example.com \\\n  --oidc-client-id fwdx-web \\\n  --oidc-client-secret ... \\\n  --oidc-redirect-url https://tunnel.example.com/auth/oidc/callback\n```\n\nHuman auth [#human-auth]\n\n```bash\nfwdx login\nfwdx whoami\nfwdx logout\n```\n\nManagement [#management]\n\n```bash\nfwdx manage tunnels --server https://tunnel.example.com\nfwdx manage domains list --server https://tunnel.example.com\nfwdx domains add my.domain --server https://tunnel.example.com\n```\n\nTunnel runtime [#tunnel-runtime]\n\n```bash\nexport FWDX_SERVER=https://tunnel.example.com\n\nfwdx tunnel create -l localhost:3000 -s app --name app\nfwdx tunnel start app\nfwdx tunnel stop app\nfwdx tunnel list\nfwdx logs app --follow\n```\n\nThe CLI provisions an agent credential automatically on first tunnel create/start and stores it locally.\n\n\n# Deployment (/docs/deployment)\n\n\n\nDeployment [#deployment]\n\nThe recommended deployment model is:\n\n1. `fwdx` server running locally on private ports\n2. nginx terminating TLS on `443` and `4443`\n3. wildcard DNS for `*.tunnel.example.com`\n\nSections [#sections]\n\n* [nginx](/docs/deployment/nginx)\n* [systemd](/docs/deployment/systemd)\n* [TLS and DNS](/docs/deployment/tls-dns)\n\n\n# nginx (/docs/deployment/nginx)\n\n\n\nnginx [#nginx]\n\nThe common layout is:\n\n* `443` -> fwdx web port\n* `4443` -> fwdx gRPC port\n\nIf you use ingress IP allowlists, start the server with trusted proxy CIDRs so `fwdx` uses the real visitor IP instead of nginx's loopback address:\n\n```bash\nfwdx serve \\\n  --trusted-proxy-cidrs 127.0.0.1/32,::1/128 \\\n  ...\n```\n\nHTTPS vhost [#https-vhost]\n\n```nginx\nserver {\n  listen 443 ssl http2;\n  listen [::]:443 ssl http2;\n  server_name tunnel.example.com *.tunnel.example.com;\n\n  ssl_certificate     /etc/letsencrypt/live/tunnel.example.com/fullchain.pem;\n  ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/tunnel.example.com/privkey.pem;\n\n  location / {\n    proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:4040;\n    proxy_http_version 1.1;\n    proxy_set_header Host $host;\n    proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;\n    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;\n    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;\n    proxy_read_timeout 86400s;\n    proxy_send_timeout 86400s;\n  }\n}\n```\n\ngRPC stream block [#grpc-stream-block]\n\n```nginx\nstream {\n  server {\n    listen 4443 ssl;\n    listen [::]:4443 ssl;\n\n    ssl_certificate     /etc/letsencrypt/live/tunnel.example.com/fullchain.pem;\n    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/tunnel.example.com/privkey.pem;\n    ssl_alpn h2;\n\n    proxy_pass 127.0.0.1:4440;\n    proxy_connect_timeout 10s;\n    proxy_timeout 86400s;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n\n# systemd (/docs/deployment/systemd)\n\n\n\nsystemd [#systemd]\n\nExample service:\n\n```ini\n[Unit]\nDescription=fwdx server\nAfter=network.target nginx.service\n\n[Service]\nType=simple\nExecStart=/usr/local/bin/fwdx serve \\\n  --hostname tunnel.example.com \\\n  --oidc-issuer https://issuer.example.com \\\n  --oidc-client-id fwdx-web \\\n  --oidc-client-secret YOUR_OIDC_SECRET \\\n  --oidc-redirect-url https://tunnel.example.com/auth/oidc/callback \\\n  --oidc-admin-emails admin@example.com \\\n  --web-port 4040 \\\n  --grpc-port 4440 \\\n  --data-dir /var/lib/fwdx\nRestart=always\nRestartSec=5\n\n[Install]\nWantedBy=multi-user.target\n```\n\nLogs:\n\n```bash\njournalctl -u fwdx -f\n```\n\n\n# TLS and DNS (/docs/deployment/tls-dns)\n\n\n\nTLS and DNS [#tls-and-dns]\n\nDNS [#dns]\n\nYou need:\n\n* `tunnel.example.com` -> server public IP\n* `*.tunnel.example.com` -> server public IP\n\nTLS [#tls]\n\nThe certificate must cover:\n\n* `tunnel.example.com`\n* `*.tunnel.example.com`\n\nIf nginx terminates TLS, fwdx itself can stay on plain local ports.\n\n\n# fwdx Docs (/docs)\n\n\n\nfwdx [#fwdx]\n\n`fwdx` is a self-hosted tunnel platform for exposing local HTTP services through your own domain.\n\nDocumentation [#documentation]\n\n* [Installation](/docs/installation)\n* [CLI Usage](/docs/cli)\n* [Deployment](/docs/deployment)\n* [Authentication](/docs/authentication)\n* [Architecture / Spec](/docs/architecture)\n\nCurrent Product Scope [#current-product-scope]\n\n* gRPC-based tunnel transport\n* Nginx-friendly deployment model\n* Admin UI and management APIs\n* Detached client tunnel runtime\n* Tunnel request stats and persisted request logs\n\nNext Rewrite Direction [#next-rewrite-direction]\n\nThe platform is being moved toward:\n\n* server-owned control-plane state\n* OIDC-based human authentication\n* separate machine credentials for client agents\n* stronger tunnel observability\n* WebSocket support\n\n\n# Client Install (/docs/installation/client)\n\n\n\nClient Install [#client-install]\n\nInstall or build the same `fwdx` binary on the client machine.\n\nSet client configuration:\n\n```bash\nexport FWDX_SERVER=https://tunnel.example.com\nexport FWDX_TUNNEL_PORT=4443\n```\n\nCreate and start a tunnel:\n\n```bash\nfwdx tunnel create -l localhost:5173 -s vite --name vite\nfwdx tunnel start vite\n```\n\nThe first tunnel create/start on a machine provisions and stores a local agent credential in `~/.fwdx/client.json`.\n\nDetached mode:\n\n```bash\nfwdx tunnel start vite --detach\nfwdx logs vite --follow\n```\n\n\n# Installation (/docs/installation)\n\n\n\nInstallation [#installation]\n\n`fwdx` has two sides:\n\n* a public server\n* one or more tunnel clients\n\nRequirements [#requirements]\n\n* Go `1.25+` to build from source\n* a Linux server with a public IP for the server side\n* a domain such as `tunnel.example.com`\n* TLS certificates for the public hostname\n\nPaths [#paths]\n\n* Server binary: `/usr/local/bin/fwdx`\n* Client config: `~/.fwdx/client.json`\n* Detached runtime state: `~/.fwdx/run`\n\nNext Steps [#next-steps]\n\n* [Install the server](/docs/installation/server)\n* [Install the client](/docs/installation/client)\n\n\n# Server Install (/docs/installation/server)\n\n\n\nServer Install [#server-install]\n\nBuild from source:\n\n```bash\ngit clone https://github.com/BRAVO68WEB/fwdx.git\ncd fwdx\ngo build -o fwdx .\nsudo mv fwdx /usr/local/bin/\n```\n\nRun behind nginx:\n\n```bash\nfwdx serve \\\n  --hostname tunnel.example.com \\\n  --oidc-issuer https://issuer.example.com \\\n  --oidc-client-id fwdx-web \\\n  --oidc-client-secret YOUR_OIDC_SECRET \\\n  --oidc-redirect-url https://tunnel.example.com/auth/oidc/callback \\\n  --oidc-admin-emails admin@example.com \\\n  --web-port 4040 \\\n  --grpc-port 4440 \\\n  --data-dir /var/lib/fwdx\n```\n\nThe web port serves proxy traffic, admin UI, OIDC callback routes, and admin APIs. The gRPC port serves tunnel clients.\n"]
